Republican strategy to counter Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
The Brennan Centre, however, considers it a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the US democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments enact new laws as of 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has grown after the November 2010 elections, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in the only year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and remove citizens with a judicial record from their right to vote.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first State to impose such a requirement.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the Indiana law.
The Republican authorities urged to extend this practice to other States.
Over the past two years, they were sponsoring bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than $100 to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters 18-29 years of age do not have the required photo identity card.
Much more.
Students, who are considered to vote more for democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID card issued by their institutions.
On the other hand, these same States allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use the cards issued by those clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no State required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are American citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Spanish vote.
It appears, however, that two out of three Spanish voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators sponsored laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to electors wishing to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to record about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other states aimed at reducing the advance voting period.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of those who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In return, the white people who made up 76% of the voters accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetos of the democratic governors.
The United States Advocate General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could have partially limited the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have adopted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undeniably make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious objective to influence results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Centre report shows that the states that have adopted these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed at the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to affirm with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the US democratic system.
