The boson of Higgs decorated
The announcement of the probable discovery of Higgs's boson created a whole emem last summer, and for cause.
We believe that this boson is involved in the mechanism responsible for the mass of all things in the Universe, nothing but that.
And then this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behaviour of the matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely sure that it is the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data released this week at a major physical congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain of it.
Let us still assume that this is the Higgs, since the chances of being mistaken seem thin, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this low world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break that rule - and don't try too hard, you're gonna hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics are a very strange world, it turns out that it also has such a law: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting of grosso modo in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists rank the particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens named fermions, who sadly obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other are bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can well be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the melons, which we will not address here, and the "particle of force," by which the great forces of nature spread and to which the boson of Higgs would in some way be related.
These bosons, we must point out here, are not all as exotic bestioles as we might believe.
In fact, if you can read this column, it is thanks to a boson of an extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric load accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, a little like a rock launched in a pond.
From this "disturbing" is born an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons "force-bearing."
More stable field
The same applies to Higgs' boson, to this difference that it is another field, Higgs' field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
This field of Higgs is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, we need to reach very, very high energies, just as if it were a frozen pond that only a very big rock could rip the surface.
This is why we need an immense accelerator of particles like that of the CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
It is not all the particles, nor all the materials, that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold of himself on a fridge.
And in the same way, not all the particles interact with the field of Higgs: those who do it have a mass, while others (like the photon, yours) do not have a mass.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to review any discrepancy between MS observations and predictions.
In fact, they are many who wish that we find it, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and close some of the holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oups!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oups!).
But we haven't found such deviations in the CERN so far.
Implications
The impact of this research on the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. Alone-the-World are more difficult to predict, but we would be wrong to assume that there will be no such research.
Here: in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories were in no way suspecting the revolution that their work was about to trigger.
They had scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already told us the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -, at the beginning the laser was rather seen as a "labo gadget."
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optics work.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original intention, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and has won it the Nobel of Physics 2009.
It does not, of course, mean that LHC's activities will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
