With Bitcoin, all the network nodes are both depositaries of the account book, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two e-mail addresses in the way of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged exist well in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It calls for the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and whose winner, sort of an interim central banker, will have the privilege to add this additional line.
This is a file hash phase, that is to say to transform a large file into a shorter and unique digital print.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "hacher" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (lots of zeros at first).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructively linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan because both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this award is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred millionth, which leaves the margin...
The challenge is also addressed at each increase in the calculation power.
