Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, it is the second member State of the former Eastern Block (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the following years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before World War II, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet an understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the conference by A. Šternfeld at the astronomical observatory in Warsaw on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his leading-edge work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics."
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and years later Šternfeld closer that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award in France for his work "Introduction à l'astronautique."
Ledit Dr Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of world-renowned astronautics, his contribution has been particularly rewarded by the fact that his name has been given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
From 1925 a draisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the draisine.
The only known information about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with teachers Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the retained documents that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research has stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author called Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
The purpose of these two projects was military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all rocket technology projects were carried out by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a question of a company in the November 1954 issue of the Problem newspaper, in which are four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautical Federation (created in 1951), and by the fall, PTA became a regular member of it.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held his office until his death in 1959.
From 1956, PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This 1800-metre rocket was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently an improved version was built, RM-1A and during the summer of 1959, two-storey rocket flight tests RM-2 were started in the Bledov desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 metres and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind in altitude.
But in 1963 all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965 succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liter, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liter and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liter.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a 10 kg payload at an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were subsequently built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
