The Argo movie: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters made up of Islamist students attacked the American Embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats in hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had been supporting his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the trust of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, which was further aggravated later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States led to a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian feeling.
The Iranian debacle made a major contribution to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered a small victory to America.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated perimeties, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran through a rocambolesque cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a tourning team who came to make markings for the filming of a large-scale film of science-fiction.
Gender combination
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, with the film based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper film," the story of a successful coup, of a traitor - for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The ambiances follow: sequences of Tehran in documentary style (in the subtitles are presented iconic photographs of the times of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been retranscribed in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes of CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his actor game ceased to raise ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark police officer "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that does not take place in his home city, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywoodian standards.
Affleck also shows this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, when rebuilding real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability when suddenly, in a given place, is written a history page.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false shooting team in Tehran's bazar).
Too many shares in too many places
The director had to be content with a subject that, in fact, offered only few picturesque scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He is doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the crisis threat at Tehran airport is discarded by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing runway are quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperatives, their characters would have deserved a greater place and they are not, far from there, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks some dramatic tension, it is seen with moderate interest, enjoying the retro design and style of the 1970s.
He leads the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in some way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated character of the representation of secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the case.
