The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that real adventures are not just about imagination. To convince themselves, just contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected book mountain - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it makes very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passenger on the bottom side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, an informatician in a large neighbouring company, tells us, "Yes, he is indeed beautiful, this building."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes voluntarily in one of these ringardes libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory city with nothing attractive at the doors of Rotterdam, has a quite special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniatures in painted concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive has remained limited.
This is how the city authorities realised that there was only one way to take over the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the office of architects of Rotterdam MVRDV, master of daring sticks diagrams and creator of buildings full of spirit and often cynical, accepted the project with its usual flegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a casing on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, disconcerted and stirring their shoulders, Maas, the fearful, emptied his books of choice in order of size to make it a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by militant arguments by a: "dear common!"
There she is, my proposal for Spijkenisse's book mountain, or as they say, Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million-euro mountain has gone out of the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and some mitoyan buildings and houses for a total of 50 houses.
In early November, the book mountain received the second "Best Library of NL 2012."
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This is how this little dull bourgade, which until today had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and a mairie with a daightening daider, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has enriched itself with a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in his history.
The long way to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Of course, an elevator brings you to the heart of the mass, but the true joys of reading and architecture open to you when you scramble the building floor at the discovery of its topography.
The interior fully made of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant reverberations speak unequivocally the language of municipal public places.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking for public benches, dogs, and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books, and still books.
"Normally, library rays are located along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," said Willy Maas.
We have completely upset the classic space configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the book mountain has been adroitantly built: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environment centre and the building's technical power plant.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes lambris, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and odorate.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want any unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," says Joop Trouborst, project leader at the town of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, the synthetic membrane of a millimeter thick has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The fine membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, in plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes colour and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 metres, the literary coffee offers us an imprenable view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pots ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute above all to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in ecology," Trouborst confides.
The building temperature is geothermal.
Although the book mountain is below a glass bell, the sun only unveils the interior, even in the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted from through to the glass facade serve as a sunscreen, intercepting much of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
The completely automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic informatician, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was there too.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" by Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has made it possible to fill the vides of the library that were not yet completely gardened (now it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing on all sides.
For the architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I think our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration. "
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity."
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, this is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose forbearance.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious because it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, but was not too critical to Israel.
At the time of the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen forbearance in the vote on the establishment of an air exclusion zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany experience difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
In addition, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore face several fronts.
We expect them to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
An external policy, as in France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for Germans in practice?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other great powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and forbearance in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to hit public opinion, but also the elites of Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining element.
However, I would not give too much importance to it, because it is not a purely unilateral relationship.
But this is at least a key element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing forbearance in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think that the fracture is not so serious that it was so in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, the views on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American internal political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration has a secret understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government of course cannot publicly defend its position.
I think the real differences of opinion are not so big that they always seem to be.
If you observe the relations between Obama and the Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from outstripping enthusiasm about Netanyahou's policy.
Is Germany having difficulties reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I think it doesn't make things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today this is not the case.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will assume a locomotive role in the future and will encourage Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that marks their independence more.
Is Germany playing an important role in the international arena, is Germany only trying to play a key role?
Or does she still have difficulties in taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable to it and, for obvious reasons, it still has difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we note that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with very varied neighbours and opinions, and this is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at this moment the EU is not filling this gap, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America together analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German policy, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
