Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial TSI include syphilis, chlamydia and blennorragy (or gonorrhea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
The lice of the pubis and the gale belong to the parasitic TSI.
What are the main groups involved?
Syphilis and blennorragy often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute considers that sexual contact between men is the source of at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidosis (fungal), blennorragy and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15-25 years.
In addition, in Germany, human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the change in the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years, from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been declining.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth from the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual disease?
Infectious diseases can cause abscess in the genitals, urinary pain, white loss, lower belly pain, and the appearance of buttons and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How to protect yourself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but do not protect 100%.
The reason is that the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close bodily contact.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who often changes sex partners take regular examinations.
Most rapidly detected TSIs can be healed and late sequelae can be avoided.
