The soldier is accused of robbing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that soldier Bradley Manning -- accused of being the source of the biggest leak of confidential information in the whole history of the American army -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims to have suffered during his military detention.
In a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, did not reveal any complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a request that the Manning case be closed on the ground that the sequestration took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of robbing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
At the Friday hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning recognized that the treatment that his guards reserved was "excellent" and that the treatment he had in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, said Fein.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about certain problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems raised.
"They wrote" no problem "(after having addressed the concerns), and however, it did not mean that I had not raised any problems," Manning said.
Military judge Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special commission that had met to evoke the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed indicating a "risk of injury."
The military stated that they had assigned it this restrictive status -- one level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for its protection and safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine, and I wanted to be removed from my status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday on his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for almost two months before being transferred to the military prison at the base of the Corps des Marines in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered suicide when he was in Kuwait and had fainted once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that he was not kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was going on in the rest of the world was very alarming.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, this cage," said Manning on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he had spent the lightest of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without a company.
Manning also added that the only objects at his disposal were mattresses, blankets, rods, clothes and glasses.
He tried to stay in motion, because sleeping or staying elongated during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also stated that when he was trying to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his Thursday testimony -- that after having been forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other detainees one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was it allowed to cover himself with a cover during the call.
