The hardest trade in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mules
For four euros, Indonesian volcano carriers are at risk of life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through spanked stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by carrying the sulphur of the volcano Kawah Ijen, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas from the insides of the earth solidifies at contact with air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of almost 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the spanked trails.
There are only 250 metres to the volcano's head that grows at 2.386 metres of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to gravel this distance, at a tortoise look, keeping the balance and measuring their steps to not drain and fall into the precipice.
They know that a fake step could cost them life, as it happened to a French tourist who made a mortal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, he spreads a way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and harshly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometres to the balance that a mining company has installed a little down at 1,850 metres altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 centimes of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry at Rs 10,000 (83 cents), since this ore is very present in daily life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and is even used to blanch sugar.
"As we transport about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips per day.
Each one takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but it allows him to win 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would win in the fields.
"The income of miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)," said the bearer who once worked as a maçon on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not so difficult, but Anto returned close to her family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java to convert her to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Ijen Kawah, but the sulphur has already started to make him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and carries special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
