The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 agents present.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the summit closed, and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The few information that was circulating between journalists was that given by press officers of some of the Unasur governments who were attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more important information.
Later, the Peru Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final statement" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech rather than the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Arab-South America Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had not circulated the declaration called also Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it is possible to verify that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but have limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which sets a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the ICJ decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial that Lima brought against Santiago and which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are holding today before this international court," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversy, treaties and international courts," said President Piñera by giving a handshake to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Covenant by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that International Tribunal, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua which it considered to be seriously mistaken.
The summit was held without the presence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the disappointment of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was asked to open the deliberations in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the action lines for 31 projects had been set between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of Unasur would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits."
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve drug accessibility, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (from Latin America) must not have a triomphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to maintain a better future for our people," said President Humala.
"We have decided to focus on a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were related to Peru and were on the cross-border axes of his territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were related to a larger connection with Ecuador, although he had not given further details.
The outcome document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will allow it to be reintegrated into the Union of South American Nations," which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional appointment, that he was hoping to meet his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a CIJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua, which will ask for a discussion with that country," he said.
"I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will resolve this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," said President Santos.
The presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the accession of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, at the summit, the Block Defence Ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of the Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
