Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globe trotter of the basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, either as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, manager and head of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I carried several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was President of the BSN, Director General of the National Team and President of the Federation during the 1990s," remembers Reyes during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for over 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remember his unstandard itinerary, testify to it.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he is most affectionate are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as co-manager or team manager.
"It was my best years, the years I enjoyed most because I had the chance to participate in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967 onwards, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a lot of satisfaction for many years, including the five championships disputed from 1971 to 1975.
I then withdrew at the 1981 championship, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the head of the team, "says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been in charge here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me, "I have a costaud player for you, he measures two meters.
Do you want it? "
That's how Mincy started, one of Puerto Rico's best players.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember he said if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He welcomed the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only remotely since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's responsibilities in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us play the last game, "said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Team the best national team you saw?
She is one of the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is that of the PanAmerican Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and put a rocket on the United States team, which was quite similar to that that that had won bronze at the World.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that might not be the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and a great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players suspended by the imbroglio of the PanAmerican Games of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all pronostics.
What was Puerto Rico's best player?
No doubt, it's about Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics at international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated this level as Piculín did.
And that without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team made up of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Avoir is part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have wanted to put in place, such as regionalization of minor categories.
For example, Ponce's boys only play in their area and face only teams from other parts of the island during national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
At least I saw the advantage of mandatory certification and courses for leaders, field staff and arbitrators.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch clips from my time on YouTube, I take advantage of my grandchildren and, from time to time, I attend basketball games.
And of course, I take advantage of my wife's company, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, was known globally by John Ross Ewing, more known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas," in which he was an unscrupulous, redundant and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnet J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who had returned this year in the role of J.R in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night from complications of cancer, according to a family release sent to The associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his dear home city of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and his close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who interpreted the role of her wife in the original series and in the aftermath, was with Hagman when he died in a hospital in Dallas, said her press attaché, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he was living life," Gray said in a press release.
The doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis at Larry Hagman in 1992 and had recognized that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he had been detected with a liver malignant tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas," Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary type in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by the NBC channel from 1965 to 1970.
In this one he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered a seductive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also played in two comedies that remained on the antenna, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among his roles at the cinema are roles well received by the critics in "Le groupe," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was thanks to his magistral interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman knew his greatest success.
The CBS series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?," invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculations around the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
As a result, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had brought together 50 million viewers.
It was J.R. 's sister-in-law Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had put her pregnant and then threatened her to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to attack her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with charismatic smile: an unhonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to intercept his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," said Hagman in 1988.
We should write, "Ci-gît l'honnête citoyen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, remembered this Friday of Hagman as a "huge man, both on the small screen and in life."
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT chain.
The recording of five episodes is already completed for the second season and a sixth is being made, informed the chain.
For now, neither the Warner nor the TNT chain have provided information on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
