A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun.
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombis, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religious professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hameçon: the end of the "great count" of the Maya calendar on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax gulf that some have nicknamed "the Armageddon of the debt" and an increasing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought that the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
If we analyse what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling, it was a very good period.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to give courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
In Temple, Deputy Professor Barry Vacker delivers the "Media, Culture and End of the World" course.
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombis, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We are analyzing this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Professor of History of Latin America Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of History of Art and Anthropology, have teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The end of the world."
"We add" 2012 "to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world did not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster," students must study, create projects and pass their final examinations.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of Revelation, which does not leave students any choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
The courses have been quite popular.
"He was completed in two hours," said Restall about his high-level student course, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the beginning of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I feel like seeing what people are able to do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religious and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a question of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Infirmary, claims to have watched all apocalyptic films.
